Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Place @butter{2%tablespoon} in a #small microwave-safe bowl{}; set aside to soften (you'll use it in Step 4). Wash and dry produce.

Core, deseed, and dice @long green pepper{1}(diced into ¼-inch pieces). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced, separating whites from greens). Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Drain and rinse @corn{1}(drained and rinsed).

Rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water. Pat shrimp or chicken dry with #paper towels{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Melt another @butter{2%tablespoon} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add green pepper and scallion whites; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @flour{1%tablespoon}; cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{1%minute}.

Slowly stir @milk{1} into pot a splash at a time until fully incorporated. Stir in @water{1 1/2%cups}.

Add potatoes, @veggie stock concentrate{2}, and half the @OLD BAY® seasoning{1/2%teaspoon} (you'll use more in the next step). Bring to a boil and cook, stirring occasionally, until potatoes are very tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> TIP: To test, pierce one piece with a fork—it should go through easily.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add shrimp or chicken; cook, stirring occasionally, until cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{}.

Meanwhile, combine softened butter, @OLD BAY® seasoning{1/4%teaspoon}, and @sugar{1/4%teaspoon} until smooth.

> TIP: If the butter is still cold, microwave for ~{10%seconds} to soften.

Taste and add more Old Bay Seasoning if desired.

Halve @demi-baguette{1} lengthwise; spread cut sides with Old Bay butter. Place, cut sides up, on a #baking sheet{}.

Toast on top rack until golden, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Once potatoes are tender, reduce heat to low and mash with a #potato masher{} or #fork{} to desired consistency.

> TIP: We recommend mashing until almost smooth, leaving a few small potato pieces for texture.

Stir in @cream cheese{2%tablespoon}, corn, and @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup} until fully incorporated and chowder is thick and creamy. If needed, stir in splashes of water until chowder reaches desired consistency (it will be very thick at this point). Season generously with salt and pepper.

Once cream cheese, corn, and Monterey Jack are fully incorporated, stir in half the shrimp or half the chicken.

Halve Old Bay toast on a diagonal if desired.

Divide chowder between #bowls{}. Garnish with scallion greens and @sour cream{1 1/2%tablespoon}. Serve with Old Bay toast on the side.

Serve remaining shrimp or remaining chicken atop bowls.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.